WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-IN

00:00:00.326 --> 00:00:06.045
In 2024, over 26,000 crores worth of health
insurance claims were rejected by insurers.

00:00:06.393 --> 00:00:07.510
But why?

00:00:07.729 --> 00:00:11.704
Well, because this is the policy copy
you get when you buy a health insurance.

00:00:11.817 --> 00:00:17.489
And if you look at it carefully, you'll find 9 hidden
clauses that make sure the insurer is not paying your bill.

00:00:17.697 --> 00:00:22.505
I even have an awful meter over here
to find out how bad they actually are.

00:00:22.852 --> 00:00:26.326
So we'll start with the first
one which is the sub limit.

00:00:26.547 --> 00:00:33.329
So let's say that you bought this policy and this
policy says that your Sum assured is 10 lakh rupees.

00:00:33.577 --> 00:00:38.371
Which means that if you get admitted to a hospital
and you get a bill of up to 10 lakh rupees

00:00:38.578 --> 00:00:40.726
the insurance provider will cover it for you.

00:00:40.945 --> 00:00:43.310
And if it crosses 10 lakhs then
you pay it from your pocket.

00:00:43.409 --> 00:00:48.882
So let's imagine you get admitted to a hospital and the
treatment for a particular disease costs like 5 lakhs.

00:00:49.337 --> 00:00:52.319
But you have a sum insured
of 10 lakhs. So you're safe, right?

00:00:52.515 --> 00:00:53.281
Wrong.

00:00:53.625 --> 00:00:59.537
In this case they would actually pay only 2
lakhs and not the 5, you would pay the rest.

00:00:59.704 --> 00:01:01.710
And the reason reason is because of sub limit.

00:01:01.893 --> 00:01:07.112
If you look over here you'll notice that this
particular disease has a sub limit of 2 lakh rupees.

00:01:07.269 --> 00:01:09.056
Which means they won't
pay you more than this.

00:01:09.229 --> 00:01:14.684
So what you have to learn from this, is if you find a health
insurance that's really cheap and has a great sum assured.

00:01:14.709 --> 00:01:17.222
And you think damn, I've gotta
buy it because it's too cheap.

00:01:17.247 --> 00:01:20.955
Maybe, it has a sub limit that
should not exist over there.

00:01:21.002 --> 00:01:23.830
This gets a 3 on 10 on the awful meter.

00:01:23.893 --> 00:01:27.266
And it gets a 3 on 10 because
if you miss the next clause,

00:01:27.533 --> 00:01:33.131
even if you don't have sub limits, the insurer
could refuse to pay up to 50% of your bill.

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:37.654
And when I was looking for it I actually
couldn't find it because it's sneaky.

00:01:37.943 --> 00:01:39.846
It's right here under room modifier.

00:01:39.933 --> 00:01:42.324
And over here it says room rent capping.

00:01:42.775 --> 00:01:48.865
Yeah, so room rent capping is probably one of the
most misunderstood clauses in an insurance contract.

00:01:49.024 --> 00:01:49.773
This is Shrehith.

00:01:49.927 --> 00:01:52.970
I first discovered him on his
amazing writing on Finshots.

00:01:53.158 --> 00:01:56.353
He also knows a lot about insurance
because he's the co founder of Ditto.

00:01:56.481 --> 00:02:02.682
Okay, so the way this works is room rent clauses
are sort of explicitly mentioned in different ways.

00:02:02.929 --> 00:02:05.348
So either you will see something like

00:02:05.768 --> 00:02:12.200
1% of your sum insured is set aside for room rent payouts.
Or you will see something like

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.552
hey listen, you can pick a room, anything you want, so long
as it's a single private AC room

00:02:18.805 --> 00:02:23.192
and in both cases, irrespective of how it
is worded, it is essentially a restriction.

00:02:23.337 --> 00:02:27.526
Now I know this may not seem like a
big deal but here is where you are wrong.

00:02:27.806 --> 00:02:30.196
Imagine the limit is 5000 rupees.

00:02:30.257 --> 00:02:32.157
And that single AC room is not available.

00:02:32.185 --> 00:02:35.456
But a deluxe room is available
which is ten thousand rupees.

00:02:35.535 --> 00:02:38.425
So you think I'll be there for three nights.

00:02:38.673 --> 00:02:39.432
Ten thousand.

00:02:39.457 --> 00:02:39.957
Ten thousand.

00:02:40.009 --> 00:02:40.515
Ten thousand.

00:02:40.585 --> 00:02:41.510
That's thirty thousand.

00:02:41.784 --> 00:02:44.005
The insurer said he has
a limit of five thousand.

00:02:44.089 --> 00:02:46.567
So they'll pay five thousand
total thirty thousand.

00:02:46.680 --> 00:02:49.586
You will actually only pay fifteen
and the insurer pay fifteen.

00:02:49.643 --> 00:02:50.143
Right?

00:02:50.251 --> 00:02:50.751
Right.

00:02:50.891 --> 00:02:52.280
Absolutely wrong.

00:02:52.435 --> 00:02:55.458
The amount you have
to pay will be 1.5 lakhs.

00:02:55.496 --> 00:03:00.171
And the insurer will pay another
1.5 lakhs for the total bill to be 3 lakhs.

00:03:00.403 --> 00:03:01.175
Let me explain.

00:03:01.267 --> 00:03:05.092
It's called proportionate
deduction and it's freaking crazy.

00:03:05.235 --> 00:03:06.316
Imagine this.

00:03:06.731 --> 00:03:08.718
You have a limit

00:03:09.690 --> 00:03:12.790
of 5,000 rupees for a room.

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:26.605
Everything else that you spend so say on surgery,
medicines, consultation etc will come to whatever bill.

00:03:26.713 --> 00:03:30.623
As long as it's within your sum
assured, the insurer will cover it.

00:03:31.129 --> 00:03:32.542
But let's change one thing here.

00:03:32.921 --> 00:03:37.769
Instead of getting a 5000 room for whatever
reason you get a 10,000 rupee room.

00:03:38.145 --> 00:03:40.060
And all these things still exist.

00:03:40.506 --> 00:03:43.036
What you just did was get
yourself a better room.

00:03:43.375 --> 00:03:46.706
But you just agreed to pay 50% of the bill.

00:03:46.823 --> 00:03:49.834
You see, the difference between
these room rents is 50%.

00:03:50.263 --> 00:03:54.890
So the insurer says I will proportionately
deduct 50% from everything.

00:03:54.990 --> 00:04:00.089
Which means if this total bill over here
is 3 lakh rupees, he will say, it was 50%.

00:04:00.417 --> 00:04:01.036
50%.

00:04:01.104 --> 00:04:01.744
50%.

00:04:01.911 --> 00:04:04.794
You pay 1.5 lakhs,
I'll pay 1.5 lakhs.

00:04:05.081 --> 00:04:06.380
The point is this.

00:04:06.673 --> 00:04:09.544
There should be no room rent capping

00:04:09.625 --> 00:04:15.487
when you get an insurance. This gets
an awful clause rating of a 4 out of 10.

00:04:16.080 --> 00:04:19.459
So take a look at this over here.

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:21.922
It's called the no claim bonus.

00:04:21.947 --> 00:04:23.194
And if you look at the no claim

00:04:23.265 --> 00:04:26.775
bonus, it'll say no claim bonus.

00:04:26.985 --> 00:04:32.137
A no claim bonus of 20% of the sum assured
for each completed and continuous policy year.

00:04:32.433 --> 00:04:34.840
This is really cool for a bunch of reasons.

00:04:34.865 --> 00:04:41.163
So let's suppose your sum assured is 10 lakh rupees
and there's a 20% over here that is a no claim bonus.

00:04:41.349 --> 00:04:43.762
So if you don't claim
anything, it becomes 12 lakhs.

00:04:43.941 --> 00:04:48.025
Then the year after that if there's no claim,
14 lakhs and then 16 lakhs and 18 lakhs.

00:04:48.197 --> 00:04:50.307
And then 20 lakhs, you get the point.

00:04:50.957 --> 00:04:52.449
But here's the problem with it.

00:04:52.669 --> 00:05:00.185
If you get the no claim bonus and your room rent is
capped at 1%, it does not automatically mean that it will

00:05:00.298 --> 00:05:05.218
now be calculated as 1% of your new
sum assured with the no claim bonus added.

00:05:05.325 --> 00:05:11.086
Instead, the actual room rent restriction of 1%
is calculated based on the actual sum assured.

00:05:11.121 --> 00:05:12.383
So bonus is not counted.

00:05:12.841 --> 00:05:17.315
And then we also have this little
thing here called the restoration benefit.

00:05:17.393 --> 00:05:20.079
Now this is sold as
this glorious thing.

00:05:20.249 --> 00:05:26.186
So let's suppose you have 10 lakh rupees as your sum assured
and you spend all of it within that period of your policy.

00:05:26.553 --> 00:05:33.846
And this restoration benefit will basically fill that up
and bring it back to 10 lakh rupees for you to use again.

00:05:33.933 --> 00:05:34.700
Sounds good, right?

00:05:34.767 --> 00:05:35.705
But it's actually not.

00:05:35.789 --> 00:05:42.967
Because sometimes these guys do not allow the
restoration amount to be reused for the same disease.

00:05:43.341 --> 00:05:50.330
I give this clause an easy 4 on 10 on the awful
meter because this is actually pretty bad.

00:05:50.493 --> 00:05:51.998
But wait till you hear the next one.

00:05:52.701 --> 00:05:53.737
Co payment.

00:05:53.957 --> 00:05:58.194
Now notice this co payment
thing is expressed in a percentage

00:05:58.508 --> 00:06:02.588
and co payment is exactly
what it sounds like, you co-pay.

00:06:02.845 --> 00:06:04.850
So over here it says 20%.

00:06:04.899 --> 00:06:10.013
This basically means if it's a 1 lakh
rupee bill, you co-pay and you pay 20% of it

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:14.530
and in return the insurance costs
a few thousand rupees less.

00:06:14.884 --> 00:06:19.189
But there's also another version of the same
idea that features in many policies these days.

00:06:19.422 --> 00:06:20.986
It's called a deductible.

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:26.407
In most cases what the insurance companies will tell you
is hey, instead of paying sort of a percentage value,

00:06:26.661 --> 00:06:32.615
you pay something every time you have to
make a claim and then whatever comes after.

00:06:32.674 --> 00:06:37.088
So the bill is 5 lakhs and
the deductible is set at 2 lakhs.

00:06:37.379 --> 00:06:41.763
You pay the 2 lakhs and the remaining 3
lakhs is paid out by the insurance company.

00:06:42.155 --> 00:06:48.741
You're buying a health insurance just so you
don't have to worry about the hospital bill.

00:06:49.147 --> 00:06:52.593
Simple solution, avoid
co payment clause.

00:06:52.931 --> 00:06:57.838
So I give this a simple 5 out of 10
on the awful clause meter.

00:06:58.229 --> 00:07:01.069
But wait till you hear
about zonal co payments.

00:07:01.237 --> 00:07:05.697
So if you open your sort of policy
terms and conditions, you may see that

00:07:06.037 --> 00:07:10.372
insurance companies will have
something like zone wise payment structure.

00:07:10.417 --> 00:07:16.877
So they'll say people in zone one will pay a certain
premium, people in zone 2 will pay certain kind of premiums

00:07:16.951 --> 00:07:19.774
and people in Zone 3 may
pay different kinds of premiums.

00:07:19.877 --> 00:07:25.074
And the reason why this happens is because insurance
companies can then use differential pricing

00:07:25.168 --> 00:07:26.908
to target people in different cities.

00:07:27.015 --> 00:07:33.450
So for Instance, if you're living in a city where
medical expenses are way below the national average,

00:07:33.792 --> 00:07:38.597
then automatically insurance companies can
come and say we offer you a lower premium

00:07:38.777 --> 00:07:42.163
simply because we don't have to
pay as much to the hospitals there.

00:07:42.495 --> 00:07:47.130
However, the challenge happens when somebody
buys the policy claiming that they're in a tier

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:50.942
3 city and then consistently
make claims in tier 1 cities.

00:07:50.995 --> 00:07:56.052
Then the insurance companies can come and say that look,
we mandate you to pay a portion of the bill yourself.

00:07:56.105 --> 00:07:59.018
So simple solution, avoid zonal co payments.

00:07:59.217 --> 00:08:00.879
Okay, this one is really important.

00:08:00.985 --> 00:08:01.975
The waiting period. The one

00:08:02.495 --> 00:08:06.969
The one that you should first know about is
the initial waiting period which is 30 days.

00:08:07.129 --> 00:08:12.856
Which means as soon as you buy your health insurance
for the first 30 days you aren't covered for anything.

00:08:12.897 --> 00:08:14.951
You just have to wait.

00:08:15.089 --> 00:08:19.425
And sometimes some spirit specific diseases
aren't covered for an X number of years.

00:08:19.450 --> 00:08:21.256
In this case over
here is three years.

00:08:21.576 --> 00:08:23.298
So make sure this is
as low as possible.

00:08:23.351 --> 00:08:26.323
But every health insurance
policy has this.

00:08:26.531 --> 00:08:28.205
So let's take a hypothetical example.

00:08:28.459 --> 00:08:33.714
Let's suppose you have a blood pressure problem and you tell
the health insurance people that yeah, I have a blood pressure

00:08:33.739 --> 00:08:37.760
issue and for some reason you have
a heart attack one year after you buy it.

00:08:37.795 --> 00:08:42.490
If they can connect your heart attack with the
blood pressure which is a pre existing disease,

00:08:42.623 --> 00:08:44.575
they basically won't give you the claim.

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:49.505
Basically this means you should buy the health
insurance when you're fit, not when you're sick.

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:52.769
But this gets a 6 on 10
on the awful clause meter.

00:08:52.979 --> 00:08:55.162
This one's really cool actually.

00:08:55.204 --> 00:08:57.985
And it's called the top up.

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:01.411
This is sold like any
Internet recharge.

00:09:01.436 --> 00:09:03.166
You have a limit of 100 GB.

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:07.471
Want to get another 50 GB top up,
scratch this card and pay 50 rupees.

00:09:07.745 --> 00:09:09.492
I know, I know we don't have
scratch cards anymore.

00:09:09.564 --> 00:09:12.952
But the same logic is for
health insurance as well.

00:09:13.057 --> 00:09:14.672
You have 10 lakh rupees.

00:09:14.715 --> 00:09:20.232
Sum assured, you can get a top up of another 10
lakh rupees bringing your grand total to 20 lakhs.

00:09:20.345 --> 00:09:21.516
But this has a big problem.

00:09:21.761 --> 00:09:24.924
Let's say your top up has
a deductible of 10 lakh rupees.

00:09:25.024 --> 00:09:30.287
It means the top up will only get activated
once the medical bill crosses 10 lakhs.

00:09:30.377 --> 00:09:33.297
Now say you get hospitalized
and the bill is 10 lakhs.

00:09:33.405 --> 00:09:35.637
This amount will be paid
by your sum insured.

00:09:35.689 --> 00:09:36.133
But now,

00:09:36.133 --> 00:09:41.362
let's say you get hospitalized again
and this time the bill is 5 lakh rupees.

00:09:41.469 --> 00:09:46.586
Now even though you have a 10 lakh rupee top
up, that is useless because the top up only gets

00:09:46.653 --> 00:09:49.195
activated if the medical bill crosses 10 lakhs.

00:09:49.341 --> 00:09:51.694
So you will have to pay
all the bill by yourself.

00:09:52.205 --> 00:09:56.184
So this clause gets a 7
on 10 on the awful meter.

00:09:56.285 --> 00:09:57.523
So what should you actually get?

00:09:57.637 --> 00:10:00.189
You should get the super top up.

00:10:00.247 --> 00:10:06.575
So instead of you having to pay the deductible
over and over again every time you make a claim,

00:10:06.765 --> 00:10:13.576
all you have to do is pay the deductible once and the
insurance company will pay out the remaining expenses.

00:10:13.689 --> 00:10:18.602
And so you don't have to worry about paying
the deductible every time you make a claim.

00:10:18.705 --> 00:10:20.552
And then we have daycare.

00:10:20.614 --> 00:10:26.728
So if I look at this over here, we can
see daycare procedures and treatments.

00:10:26.825 --> 00:10:30.411
Over here it says all procedures
are covered up to annual sum insured.

00:10:30.521 --> 00:10:35.651
Basically it means if you have to get hospitalized,
but it's not 24 hours, it's something that

00:10:35.791 --> 00:10:40.419
you're in a procedure for a few hours or
basically in daycare less than 24 hours.

00:10:40.461 --> 00:10:47.535
This could be say cataract or
dialysis or tons of other things.

00:10:47.709 --> 00:10:50.924
Then does the insurer actually
cover it or not?

00:10:51.007 --> 00:10:54.744
Because these are valid procedures that are affecting
your health and the insurance must cover it.

00:10:54.845 --> 00:10:56.512
But some of them don't.

00:10:56.661 --> 00:10:57.161
Why?

00:10:57.213 --> 00:11:02.697
Because they had a clause over here that says
you must be hospitalized for at least 24 hours

00:11:02.741 --> 00:11:08.331
before you cover it, which basically means that
the health insurer is not covering daycare.

00:11:08.365 --> 00:11:10.846
Not covering this
would be very sneaky.

00:11:10.877 --> 00:11:16.151
And I would give that clause a easy
7 on 10 on the awful clause meter.

00:11:16.196 --> 00:11:18.559
And now we have

00:11:27.140 --> 00:11:28.971
cashless and reimbursement.

00:11:29.451 --> 00:11:30.204
But what is it?

00:11:30.403 --> 00:11:36.874
A few years back, what would generally happen is insurance
companies would automatically force you to pay the bill yourself.

00:11:36.955 --> 00:11:42.380
So first you pay the hospital, then you wait for a
few weeks, and then the insurance company eventually

00:11:42.443 --> 00:11:46.329
says, I'll pay out that money to you
because you paid the hospital.

00:11:46.451 --> 00:11:52.891
Now, unfortunately, this isn't very easy for the customer,
especially when they're dealing with a medical crisis.

00:11:52.935 --> 00:11:55.672
So nowadays most insurance companies offer you a cashless benefit,

00:11:57.340 --> 00:12:02.301
which basically means that you don't have to collate
all the bills, the medical documents, none of that.

00:12:02.413 --> 00:12:04.268
Instead the hospital
will do it for you.

00:12:04.383 --> 00:12:10.144
They'll send it to the insurance companies, they'll get approval
and then the insurance company will pay the hospital directly.

00:12:10.245 --> 00:12:13.181
So you don't have to pay
anything out of pocket.

00:12:13.349 --> 00:12:20.832
But imagine you have an accident and they take you to the nearest
hospital, and over there, that hospital is not a network partner.

00:12:21.009 --> 00:12:25.235
Therefore you can't use this and you
have to foot the bill yourself.

00:12:25.665 --> 00:12:26.976
Why would you do that?

00:12:27.065 --> 00:12:30.095
I'll give this an 8 on 10
on the awful clause meter.

00:12:30.529 --> 00:12:33.532
And the most evil clause
is right over here.

00:12:33.961 --> 00:12:34.641
It's.

00:12:35.025 --> 00:12:36.542
I can't even spot it.

00:12:36.601 --> 00:12:37.528
It's that small.

00:12:37.557 --> 00:12:39.066
There's a star over here.

00:12:39.161 --> 00:12:43.294
And if you see the end, it says
reasonable and necessary.

00:12:43.401 --> 00:12:44.431
Here's what it means.

00:12:44.601 --> 00:12:49.256
So unfortunately in India we don't have
something called as a standard rate card.

00:12:49.281 --> 00:12:54.889
Affectively because every hospital choose what they
believe is a fair price for a certain treatment.

00:12:54.957 --> 00:12:56.497
So hospital can overcharge.

00:12:56.557 --> 00:13:00.200
And an insurance company may have no
other recourse except to pay up.

00:13:00.501 --> 00:13:04.607
So what insurance companies do is within their
terms &amp; conditions, they have a standard clause.

00:13:04.717 --> 00:13:08.940
They say, look, we only pay for costs that
are deemed customary and reasonable.

00:13:09.021 --> 00:13:12.236
Reasonable means the cost
must be deemed reasonable.

00:13:12.277 --> 00:13:16.252
If you have injury to your shoulder or
you need surgery to the shoulder.

00:13:16.277 --> 00:13:17.020
It can't be that.

00:13:17.045 --> 00:13:22.889
The treatment and the surgery cost add upto 25 lakhs. Anywhere
across India you'll probably end up paying 2-3 lakhs.

00:13:23.031 --> 00:13:26.792
Anything beyond that sum may be
completely unreasonable.

00:13:26.887 --> 00:13:27.255
Right?

00:13:27.255 --> 00:13:30.645
So we will only pay for costs
that are deemed reasonable.

00:13:30.839 --> 00:13:32.402
What a customary is.

00:13:32.567 --> 00:13:39.848
So let's suppose the hospital decides to add a bunch of ancillary
charges that have no relation to the actual treatment, right?

00:13:40.111 --> 00:13:44.158
So the insurance companies will
always ask do doctors administer this?

00:13:44.198 --> 00:13:45.146
Do they do this?

00:13:45.342 --> 00:13:46.418
Is this the treatment protocol?

00:13:46.463 --> 00:13:52.629
So they look at that and then if the charges are not
deemed customary, then insurance companies can also say,

00:13:52.742 --> 00:13:54.328
hey look, we are not going to pay out.

00:13:54.679 --> 00:13:57.743
Now who decides what is
reasonable &amp; customary?

00:13:57.870 --> 00:14:02.622
Unfortunately, the way it works is insurance
companies generally decide what is reasonable

00:14:02.654 --> 00:14:04.992
in customary and most customers have no recourse.

00:14:05.590 --> 00:14:10.462
One minute you are saying, if I broke
my leg and I'm admitted at the hospital.

00:14:10.487 --> 00:14:16.008
I need to go and check their rate card with other
people to find out if it's reasonable or necessary.

00:14:16.033 --> 00:14:19.765
I'll say reduce ₹500 because my
insurer won't give me the payment.

00:14:19.857 --> 00:14:27.121
And just because of this, I'll call this a 10
on 10 on the awful no on the evil scorecard.

00:14:27.241 --> 00:14:30.018
But the question is, how
can you safeguard yourself?

00:14:30.129 --> 00:14:33.266
Well, here are three things that you
should know to protect yourself.

00:14:33.447 --> 00:14:34.606
Pause this video to read them.

